yoruba_text: Àsẹ̀yìnwá-à sẹ̀yìnbọ̀, mo gba à yè lá ti kó òun à ti à wọn ọmọ lọ síLuanda, níbi tí à wọn ọmọ mi obìnrin à gbà méjèèjì, Teresa à ti Joana, ti tọ́jú wọn.
english_text: Eventually, I was able to get permission for her and the children to be evacuated to Luanda, where my two older daughters, Teresa and Joana, took care of them.

yoruba_text: NiLuanda, ṣaaju ki awọn ẹrú tó wọnu ọkọ oju-omi ti ń lọ si awọn ilẹ tí Spain ati Portugal tẹ̀dó, ni Boxer fikun un, “a ń kó wọn lọ si ṣọọṣi ti o wà nito si... nibẹ ni alufaa ṣọọṣi kan yoo sì ti baptisi wọn ní ọ̀wọ̀ọ̀wọ́ ọgọrọọrun lẹẹkan.”
english_text: In Luanda, before slaves boarded ships bound for Spanish and Portuguese colonies, adds Boxer, “they were taken to a nearby church... and there baptised by a parish priest in batches of hundreds at a time.”

yoruba_text: Nígbà tí wọ́n lọ fi mí sẹ́wọ̀n ní ọdún 1961, à wùjọ kéékèèké mẹ́rin ló para pọ̀ jẹ́ ìjọ tó wà níLuandanígbà náà.
english_text: When I was taken away to prison in 1961, the congregation in Luandaconsisted of four small groups.

yoruba_text: Nito otọ, ẹ̀ka iṣẹ ijihin-isin gan-an ní awọn ẹrú tirẹ fúnraarẹ̀; ile awọn ọkunrin ajẹ́jẹ̀ẹ́ anìkà nd ágbé Jesuit kan ni Loanda [ti i ṣeLuandanisinsinyi, olu-ilu Angola] ni a fun ni 12,000.
english_text: Indeed, the very mission possessed slaves of its own; a Jesuit monastery at Loanda [now Luanda, the capital of Angola] was endowed with 12,000.

yoruba_text: Níkẹyìn, wọ́n tú wa sílẹ̀ ní August 1958, nígbà tí a sì padà déLuanda, a bá à wùjọ à wọn Ẹlẹ́rìí Jèhófà kékeré kan.
english_text: We were finally set free in August 1958, and on returning to Luanda, we found a small group of Jehovah's Witnesses.

yoruba_text: Lá papọ̀, à wọn Kristẹni alà gbà mẹ́tà dínlógójì lá tiLuandani wọ́n kó lọ sí São Nicolau.
english_text: Altogether, 37 Christian elders from Luandawere arrested and sent to São Nicolau.

yoruba_text: Ọdún tó tẹ̀ lé e ni wọ́n tú mi sílẹ̀, ní September 1970, mo sì tún dara pọ̀ mọ́ ìdílé mi à ti gbogbo à wọn ará níLuanda.
english_text: I was released the following year, in September 1970, and was reunited with my family and all the brothers in Luanda.

yoruba_text: Ní June 25, 1961, à wọn sójà já wọ ibi tí a ti ń ṣèpà dé Kristẹni níLuanda, Àǹgólà.
english_text: On June 25, 1961, soldiers broke up our Christian meeting in Luanda, Angola.

english_text: “You should all speak in agreement,” exhorts Paul.

english_text: After two yearsinjail, the apostle Paul now stood before the ruler of the Jews, Herod Agrippa II.

yoruba_text: Àpọ́sítélì Pọ́ọ̀lùsọ bó ti ṣe pà tàkì tó, ó ní: “Ẹ má ṣe máa ṣà níyàn nípa ohunkóhun, ṣùgbọ́n nínú ohun gbogbo nípasẹ̀ à dúrà à ti ìrawọ́ ẹ̀bẹ̀ pa pọ̀ pẹ̀lú ìdúpẹ́ kí ẹ máa sọ à wọn ohun tí ẹ ń tọrọ di mímọ̀ fún Ọlọ́run; à là áfíà Ọlọ́run tí ó ta gbogbo ìrònú yọ yóò sì máa ṣọ́ ọkàn-à yà yín à ti agbá ra èrò orí yín nípasẹ̀ Kristi Jésù.”
english_text: The apostle Paul drew attention to the value of this provision, saying: “Do not be anxious over anything, but in everything by prayer and supplication along with thanksgiving let your petitions be made known to God; and the peace of God that excels all thought will guard your hearts and your mental powers by means of Christ Jesus.”

yoruba_text: Wọ́n fi wọ́n ṣẹ̀sín, wọ́n parọ́ mọ́ wọn, à wùjọ èèyà nkéèyàn ń lé wọn ká àki ri, wọ́n lùwọ́n nílùkulù.
english_text: They were ridiculed and slandered, chased by mobs, and subjected tobeatings.

yoruba_text: Nígbà tí à pọ́sítélì Pọ́ọ̀lùwà lẹ́wọ̀n ní Róòmù, ó fi ìrẹ̀lẹ̀ sọ fá wọn Kristẹni ẹlẹgbẹ́ rẹ̀ pé kí wọ́n máa gbà dúrà fún òun.

english_text: There hewouldhave unusual opportunities to give a bold witness before the authorities.

yoruba_text: Fún ìdí yìí, ọ̀rọ̀ ìyà njú tí Pọ́ọ̀lùfi parí ọ̀rọ̀ rẹ̀ sí à wọn ará Kọ́ríń tì bá a mu wẹ́kú lónìí bí ó ti rí ní ẹgbẹ̀rún ọdún méjì sẹ́yìn, ó ní: “Níto rí náà, ẹ̀yin ará mi olùfẹ́ ọ̀wọ́n, ẹ fẹsẹ̀ múlẹ̀ ṣinṣin, ẹ di alá ìṣeéṣínípò, kí ẹ máa ní púpọ̀ rẹpẹtẹ lá ti ṣe nígbà gbogbo nínú iṣẹ́ Olúwa, ní mímọ̀ pé òpò yín kì í ṣe as án ní ìsopọ̀ pẹ̀lú Olúwa.”—1 Kọ́ríń tì 15:58.
english_text: Hence, Paul's final exhortation to the Corinthians is as appropriate today as it was two thousand years ago: “Consequently, my beloved brothers, become steadfast, unmovable, always having plenty to do in the work of the Lord, knowing that your labor is not in vain in connection with the Lord.”—1 Corinthians 15:58.

yoruba_text: Níto rí pé tọkà ntara ni Pọ́ọ̀lùfi wà ásù ìhìn rere, ó ṣeé ṣe fún un lá ti sọ tayọ̀tayọ̀ pé: “Mo pè yín ṣe ẹlẹ́rìí ní òní yìí gan-an pé ọrùn mi mọ́ kúrò nínú ẹ̀jẹ̀ ènìyàn gbogbo.”

yoruba_text: Iṣẹ́ méjì ni mo ń ṣe lóru, mo sì tún ń là kàkà lá ti lọ síléèwé lọ́sàn-án.
english_text: I worked two jobs at night and struggled to go to school during theday.

yoruba_text: Lọ́sàn-ánFriday, à sọyé tá a kọ́kọ́ máa gbọ́ ni “'Àwa Ti Rí Mèsá yà'!”
english_text: On Fridayafternoonthe first talk is “'We Have Found the Messiah'!”

yoruba_text: Àsọyé náà “Máa Tọ̀ Mí Lẹ́yìn,” la máa gbọ́ kẹ́yìn lọ́sàn-ánSaturday.
english_text: The day ends with a convention highlight, the talk “Come Be My Follower.”

yoruba_text: Ìwà ásù Lọ́sàn-ánSunday
english_text: Sunday Afternoon Preaching

yoruba_text: lọ́sàn-án
english_text: in the afternoon

yoruba_text: Ó ń fún mi lá yọ̀ lá ti mọ pé mo ti sin Jèhófà lá ti òwúrọ̀ ṣúlẹ̀, à ti pé mo tún máa ṣe ohun kán náà lọ́la, lọ́tùn-ún-la, à ti títí lọ.
english_text: It is satisfying to know that I have served Jehovah all day long and that I will do the same tomorrow, the day after tomorrow, and so forth.

yoruba_text: lọ́tùn-ún-la
english_text: on the day after tomorrow
